&gt; &gt;To understand a gzipped ARC file, you either have to have an index or
&gt; &gt;you must parse and uncompress it from the beginning.  There&#39;s no going
&gt; &gt;into the middle of it and finding the headers.  While it&#39;s not the
&gt; &gt;integrity of the file that is destroyed, it does make index-less work on
&gt; &gt;the file a lot harder.
&gt; &gt;  
&gt; &gt;
&gt; Isn&#39;t it true that whether or not the ARC is compressed, you can&#39;t
&gt; just go into the middle of an ARC and reliably pick up the parse. Is
&gt; there a use case for why you want to do such a thing?

It&#39;s true that you can&#39;t do it 100% reliably, but you can get really
close with a good regexp (unless you happen to have ARC files in your
ARC file:).

You might only have part of a file after a disk crash.  There might have
been an error in the offset you were given into the file.  You might
want to quickly find the last entry.  You might want to see what other
entries are just around one entry.  

I just like the Software Tools philosophy of keeping things so simple
that it&#39;s easy to make unforeseen uses of it.

-Lars
